<h3>
    Border Sides
</h3>

    <p>
        There are four(4) sides to each border-element: 
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            border-top
        </li>
        <li>
            border-right
        </li>
        <li>
            border-bottom
        </li>
        <li>
            border-left
        </li>
    </ul>
    
<p>
    Each side has its own styling, being independent from the others. If border-style is 
    defined, it acts differently based on how many arguments are supplied. 
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Four(4) Values
        <ul style="border-style: dotted solid groove double; border-color: blue green purple red">
            <li>dotted - solid - groove - double</li>
            <li>top, right, bottom, left</li>
            <li>Each position matches the index of the argument</li>
            <li>top = dotted, right = solid, bottom = groove, left = double</li>
            
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        Three(3) Values
        <ul style="border-style: dotted solid groove; border-color: blue red green">
            <li>dotted - solid - groove</li>
            <li>top, right -- left, bottom </li>
            <li>Right and left share the middle argument </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        Two(2) Values
        <ul style="border-style: dotted solid; border-color: red blue">
            <li>dotted - solid</li>
            <li>
                top -- bottom, right -- left
            </li>
            <li>
                top and bottom share the first argument, while left and right share the second
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        One(1) Value
        <ul style="border-style: dotted; ">
            <li>dotted</li>
            <li>
                top -- bottom -- right -- left
            </li>
            <li>They all take on the only one(1) value</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>
<p >
    This can be done with all the properties and not just the border-style. 
    It also works with border-color, which is how these examples were made. 
</p>

